'''Gunnar Bakke''' (born 24 October 1959) is a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] politician for the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], and the [[Bergen#Administration|mayor]] of [[Bergen]] between 2007-2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bergen.kommune.no/politikk/byradet/gunnar-bakke-frp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-20 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130413233241/https://www.bergen.kommune.no/politikk/byradet/gunnar-bakke-frp |archivedate=2013-04-13 |df= }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Bakke was born in the city of [[Bergen]].<ref name=bkomm>{{cite web|url=https://www.bergen.kommune.no/portal/page/portal/bkinternet/subpage3?id=T6892&m2_mode=&k1_mode=hide&m3_mode=spot2&re1_mode=spot1&re2_mode=spot2&re3_mode=artcenter&sectionId=986|title=Gunnar Bakke (Frp) - Ordfører|work=Bergen Kommune|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716051729/https://www.bergen.kommune.no/portal/page/portal/bkinternet/subpage3?id=T6892&m2_mode=&k1_mode=hide&m3_mode=spot2&re1_mode=spot1&re2_mode=spot2&re3_mode=artcenter&sectionId=986|archivedate=2011-07-16|df=}}</ref> He was [[chief executive officer|CEO]] of the bakery chain [[Baker Brun]] until mid-2007,<ref name="bakeri1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bakeri.net/index.php?page_id=89&article_id=2439|title=Berntsen ny leder i Vestlandske|accessdate=2007-11-18|publisher=Bakeri.net|year=2007|language=Norwegian|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209121140/http://www.bakeri.net/index.php?page_id=89&article_id=2439|archivedate=2012-02-09|df=}}</ref> and former board leader of [[Gaia Trafikk]]<ref name="nrk1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/hordaland/1.451000|title=HSD kan sverte Gaia|accessdate=2007-11-18|publisher=NRK.no|year=2006|author=Kristian Hovstad, Andreas Grimsæth|language=Norwegian}}</ref> which was the largest public transportation provider in [[Bergen]] and [[Os, Hordaland|Os]] until it merged with [[Hardanger Sunnhordlandske Dampskipsselskap|HSD]] in 2006, forming [[Tide (transportation company)|Tide]]. In 2010 he became Patron of the [[Scotland|Scottish]]-based, global street-paper network [[International Network of Street Papers]], being noticed for his support of the local Bergen-based street-paper ''[[Megafon (street paper)|Megafon]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://streetnewspapers.wordpress.com/2010/01/29/bergen-mayor-becomes-patron-of-scottish-based-global-street-paper-network/|title=Bergen Mayor becomes Patron of Scottish-based, global street-paper network|work=Newspaper Association|date=29 January 2010}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

He is married, has one child, and is educated as a [[baker]].<ref name=bkomm/>

==Political career==
Bakke has been active in local politics since 1989, and has held numerous offices at municipal and county level for the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]], including member of the [[Bergen]] city council from 1995 to 2007, and [[Hordaland]] county council since 2003. In 2007 he became mayor of Bergen, the [[List of mayors of Bergen|first for the Progress Party in the city]].<ref name=bkomm/><ref name="vg1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=177423|title=Gunnar Bakke valgt til ny ordfører i Bergen|accessdate=2007-11-18|publisher=vg.no|year=2007|author=NTB|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

