{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}

'''Lars Bertmar''' (born 1945) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] businessman who was [[CEO]] and [[Board of Directors|Chairman]] of [[investment bank]] [[Carnegie Investment Bank|Carnegie]]. He holds a [[PhD]] and is a lecturer at [[Stockholm School of Economics]].

He graduated from the Stockholm School of Economics in 1977.<ref>[http://www.hhs.se/Library/SSEpublications/Dissertations/Pages/Dissertations1946-1997.aspx ''Kapitaltillväxt, kapitalstruktur och räntabilitet: en analys av svenska industriföretag''], Lars Bertmar, Göran Molin, 1977</ref>
After working for different companies, including being vice president at [[Handelsbanken]], Bertmar became [[CEO]] of Carnegie in 1990. After 13 years as CEO, he stepped down, being replaced by [[Karin Forseke]], and was instead elected Chairman of the company. He resigned in 2006 and was replaced by [[Christer Zetterberg]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagensps.se/artiklar/import/2006/1/12/5151/index.xml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-04-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017152637/http://www.dagensps.se/artiklar/import/2006/1/12/5151/index.xml |archivedate=2010-10-17 |df= }}</ref>

He is also a member of the [[Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences]].<ref>http://www.iva.se/upload/VB-Eng2006.pdf</ref>

